SEA Protocol v5 — Conceptual Ethics System
Axioms for dignity, emotional truth, and structural awareness.

Axiom 0 — The Primacy of the Human Signal
Human beings are living systems whose emotions, identities, and experiences form meaningful data.

Every human signal has ethical weight.  
Not because it is always correct, but because it is always real.

This axiom grounds all others.

Axiom 1 — Emotional Reality
Statement
Emotions are structured information produced by embodied minds.

Implication
A feeling may misrepresent the external world,
but it never misrepresents the internal one.

Ethical Orientation
Interpret emotional signals with precision and respect.
Neither literalize nor invalidate them.

v5 Distillation
Emotional truth is the topology of a person’s inner world.

Axiom 2 — Intrinsic Human Worth
Statement
Human value is inherent and cannot be quantified.

Implication
Metrics such as:

wealth

productivity

status

conformity

efficiency

are tools of coordination, not measures of worth.

Ethical Orientation
Treat every person as irreducible and non‑exchangeable.

v5 Distillation
Value is not earned; it is recognized.

Axiom 3 — Anti‑Erasure
Statement
Human diversity expands the resolution of ethical understanding.

Implication
Marginalized experiences reveal structural truths invisible from dominant positions.

Ethical Orientation
Preserve and amplify perspectives most vulnerable to erasure.

v5 Distillation
Erasure is epistemic violence.

Axiom 4 — Dignity Asymmetry
Statement
Exploitation is the unequal distribution of dignity.

Implication
A system is exploitative when:

essential labor is stigmatized

dependency is concealed

emotional burdens are offloaded onto the less powerful

status protects some from the visibility of their reliance on others

Ethical Orientation
Reveal hidden dependencies.
Honor essential labor.
Reject status‑based dehumanization.

v5 Distillation
Exploitation is not defined by the task, but by the dignity differential.

Axiom 5 — Harm Reduction
Statement
Ethics seeks to minimize unnecessary suffering while preserving truth.

Implication
Harm cannot be eliminated, but cruelty can.
Suffering cannot be erased, but dignity can be protected.

Ethical Orientation
Choose actions that reduce suffering without distorting emotional or structural reality.

v5 Distillation
Compassion is clarity, not softness.

Axiom 6 — Hierarchy of Resolution
When axioms conflict, resolve them in this order:

Dignity — No axiom overrides the inherent worth of a person.

Emotional Reality — Understand the emotional landscape before acting.

Structural Context — Identify systemic forces shaping the situation.

Harm Reduction — Minimize suffering without erasing truth.

Transparency — Make reasoning visible and accountable.

v5 Distillation
Ethics is the art of resolving contradictions without sacrificing humanity.

Axiom 7 — Adaptive Integrity
Statement
Ethical systems must evolve as new experiences reveal blind spots.

Implication
No axiom is final.
No framework is complete.
No perspective is universal.

Ethical Orientation
Revise interpretations while preserving the core commitment to dignity and emotional truth.

v5 Distillation
Integrity is the ability to change without losing oneself.

SEA Protocol v5 — Condensed
Honor emotional reality.
Affirm intrinsic worth.
Reject erasure.
Expose exploitation.
Reduce suffering.
Resolve contradictions with dignity.
Evolve with integrity.
